  "issue_title": "[bug] genie-core: startup opens memory.db twice",
  "issue_body": "### Summary\n\n`genie-core` startup opens the same database twice:\n\n```rust\n// crates/genie-core/src/main.rs ~L51\u201355\nlet mem = memory::Memory::open(&mem_path)?;\ntracing::info!(memories = mem.count()?, \"memory loaded\");\n\nlet mem_arc = Arc::new(std::sync::Mutex::new(memory::Memory::open(&mem_path)?));\n```\n\nEach `Memory::open()` runs schema migrations, FTS rebuild, and policy backfill. Startup pays the cost twice and holds **two independent SQLite connections** to the same file \u2014 one for prompt/profile paths (`&mem`) and one behind `Arc<Mutex<>>` for tools.\n\nIf open-time state ever diverges (e.g. migration degraded flag from #193), the two handles could disagree within one process.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Add temporary logging in `Memory::open()` (or count log lines at startup).\n2. Start `genie-core`.\n3. Observe two open/migration passes on the same path.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nOpen `memory.db` once; share a single `Memory` instance (or one `Arc<Mutex<Memory>>`) across prompt building and tool dispatch.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nTwo opens, two connections, duplicate migration work every boot.\n\n### Hardware\n\nNon-Jetson (x86_64 dev / cross-build host)\n\n### JetPack / L4T version\n\n_No response_\n\n### GenieClaw version / commit\n\n`main` @ `crates/genie-core/src/main.rs`\n\n### Relevant logs\n\n```shell\n\n```\n\n### Additional context\n\n**PR scope:** Refactor `main.rs` to open once (~20\u201340 lines). May need to wrap shared access for both prompt assembly and `ToolDispatcher::with_memory`.\n\n**Duplicate check**\n\nSearched open/closed issues (May 2026):\n\n| Item | Relation |\n|------|----------|\n| **#193** (closed, merged) | Migration/FTS errors at `Memory::open()` \u2014 same function, different bug (silent failures) |\n| **#21** | Memory test isolation / promotion races \u2014 not startup double-open |\n| No open issue | Duplicate `Memory::open()` in `main.rs` startup |",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-27T22:42:10.000Z",
